    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Bridge Too Flawed?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Barbara Cohig letter suggests New York State give tax incentives to people who live within walking distance of work, as alternative to spending $4 billion to replace Tappan Zee Bridge (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Rather than spending $4 billion to expand highway capacity by replacing the Tappan Zee Bridge, which would have the ultimate effect of expanding sprawl over thousands of acres of farm and woodlands in Orange County, perhaps the Pataki administration should spend that money by giving tax incentives to people for living within walking, biking or public-transportation distance of their jobs (news article, Jan. 12).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Rather than spending $4 billion to expand highway capacity by replacing the Tappan Zee Bridge, which would have the ultimate effect of expanding sprawl over thousands of acres of farm and woodlands in Orange County, perhaps the Pataki administration should spend that money by giving tax incentives to people for living within walking, biking or public-transportation distance of their jobs (news article, Jan. 12).</p>
        <p>These tax incentives would go a long way toward revitalizing our inner cities.</p>
        <p>BARBARA COHIG  Nyack, N.Y., Jan. 12, 2000</p>
      </block>
